>mere</i> ‘lake, pond’. A daughter of Sir David <i>Hanmer</i>, a Welsh judge in the 14th century, was married to the Welsh ruler Owen Glendower, who led the revolt against Henry IV's rule in Wales.","English: habitational name from Anmer (Norfolk), from Old English <i>æned</i> ‘duck’ + <i>mere</i> ‘lake, pond’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Philip de Hanmer was born about 1300, in Hanmer, Wrexham, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Upton Macclesfield de Hanmer, was 24 and his mother, Hawise verch Einion, was 21. He married Agnes verch Dafydd about 1326, in Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1328, at the age of 29."},"et":{"Abt 1300–1328":"umbes 1300–1328","1300–1328":"1300–1328","–Male":"Surnud","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","1328–1388":"1328–1388","1332–1387":"1332–1387","–Female":"Surnud","1307–Male":"1307–Surnud","1308–Female":"1308–Surnud","1309–Female":"1309–Surnud","1277–1308":"1277–1308","1280–1300":"1280–1300","aft 1300":"pärast 1300","ABT 1326":"umbes 1326","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","Abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1388":"1388","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1387":"1387","1332":"1332","1309":"1309","1308":"1308","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","Carnarvon Castle, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Carnarvon Castle, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Ellesmere, Flintshire, Wales":"Ellesmere, Flintshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Hanmer, Flintshire, Wales":"Hanmer